07797nam a22008655i 9789814951210DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222021si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898149512107 a10.1355/97898149512102doi  a(DE-B1597)614036  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 4aHM821b.I43 2021 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a30522300aInequality and Exclusion in Southeast Asia :bAspirations of Singapore Islamic Old Fractures, New FrontiersStudies Graduates and the Challenges /ced. by Hwok Aun Lee, Christopher Choong. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2022] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbout the Contributors -- t1. Introduction: Inequality and Exclusion in Southeast Asia -- t2. Cambodia’s Experiences in Addressing Inequality -- t3. Inequality and Exclusion in Post-Soeharto Indonesia -- t4. Inequality and Exclusion in Malaysia: Macro Trends, Labour Market Dynamics and Gender Dimensions -- t5. Inequality in Myanmar: Structural Change, Policy Outcomes and Gender Dimensions -- t6. Structural Inequality in the Philippines: Oligarchy, Economic Transformation and Current Challenges to Development -- t7. Inequality and the Social Compact in Singapore: Macro Trends vs Lived Inequalities -- t8. Inequality in Thailand: Income, Socio-economic and Wealth Dimensions -- t9. Trends and Drivers of Inequality in Vietnam -- t10. Conclusion: Old Fractures and New Frontiers -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInequality is a defining global issue of our times. Southeast Asia stands out in some ways; the 2010s have seen most countries in the region reduce income gaps. Nonetheless, inequality levels remain high, especially in the middle-income to high-income countries, and popular disaffection and economic anxiety prevail, even while official statistics may paint more buoyant scenarios. The age-old problem of group-based exclusion in the development process manifests in new ways. This book provides up-to-date overviews of inequality levels and trends, primarily related to income, but also wealth and other socio-economic variables pertaining to education and health. The country chapters also examine salient themes of inequality, especially structural changes and public policies to redress inequality and exclusion, labour market developments, population groups, regional dynamics, and informal economies. We gain an appreciation for the unique conditions and diverse experiences of each country, and draw comparative insights across the region. “This is an impressive collection of papers written by scholars from Southeast Asia and addressing an important set of issues which deserve serious attention from policymakers. Inequality and social exclusion are problems which never seem to go away, even in the high-income countries, and this collection will be valuable for all those seeking to understand how serious the situation is in eight Southeast Asian states. The editors are to be congratulated on bringing together such a timely book.” Anne Booth, Emeritus Professor of Economics, School of Oriental and African Studies “This compilation of recent research on Southeast Asian economic inequalities by Lee and Choong underscores the rapid progress being made. The authors from the region underscore the global shift in research and policy attention in this century. Reflecting data and methodological diversity, the book variedly captures some ‘intersectionality’ of inequalities beyond the old focus on interpersonal and household income distribution.” Jomo KS, Fellow, Academy of Science, Malaysia “In societies across the world, rising inequality has become a critical issue over the past generation. Besides basic issues of justice, inequality between people obstructs the collective decision-making needed for societies to progress. This book is the most comprehensive study of inequality in Southeast Asia. It stresses that each society is different, but the solutions are common—good data, proper understanding, multidimensional approaches, strong institutions and popular agency.” Pasuk Phongpaichit, Emeritus Professor, Chulalongkorn University  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aEqualityzSoutheast Asia. 0aMarginality, SocialzSoutheast Asia. 4aAsian History. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aChheang, Vannarith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoong, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoong, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCruz, Jerik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuc Phung, Tung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlutting, Jana Rue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHtun, Aung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuyen Dang, Trang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHwok Aun, Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKanayde, S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeo, Piseth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Hwok Aun, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOo, Zaw, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeng, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTuaño, Philip Arnold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVanitcharearnthum, Vimut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo